Vladimir Putin and the risk of a Third World War
SAN FRANCISCO – Russia's invasion of Ukraine on February 24 marked the beginning of a third world war that has the potential to destroy our civilization.
The invasion was preceded by a long meeting between Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping on February 4 – at the start of Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Winter Olympics in Beijing.
At the end of this meeting, the two men published a 5,000-word document, carefully written, announcing a close partnership between their two countries.
The document is stronger than any treaty and certainly required meticulous preparatory negotiations.
I was surprised to see that Xi seems to have given Putin a free hand to invade and go to war with Ukraine.
He must be very confident and consider his confirmation as China's leader for life later in the year a mere formality.
After concentrating all power in his hands, Xi carefully prepared the scenario in which he would be elevated to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
After obtaining Xi's support, Putin set out to realize his lifelong dream with incredible brutality.
At the approach of his 70th birthday, Putin believes that if he wants to leave his mark on Russian history, it's now or never.
But its conception of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
It seems to believe that the Russian people need a tsar they can follow blindly.
This is precisely the opposite of a democratic society - and it's a vision that distorts the 'Russian soul', emotional to the point of sentimentality.
As a child, I met many Russian soldiers when they occupied Hungary in 1945.
I learned that they were willing to share their last piece of bread with you if you asked for it.
Later, at the beginning of the 1980s, I embarked on what I call my political philanthropy.
First, I created a foundation in my native Hungary, then I actively participated in the disintegration of the Soviet empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, disintegration had already begun.
I created a foundation in Russia, then I did the same in each of the successor states.
In Ukraine, I created a foundation even before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984, where I was the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation (which I closed in 1989, just before the Tiananmen Square massacre).
I don't know Putin personally, but I've observed his rise closely, being aware of his cruelty.
He has reduced the capital of Chechnya, Grozny, to rubble. And he threatens to do the same with the capital of Ukraine, Kyiv.
Putin was once a skilled KGB operator, but he seems to have changed recently.
Having developed a fixed idea, he seems to have lost touch with reality.
He certainly misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He expected the Russian-speaking Ukrainians to welcome the Russian soldiers with open arms, but they turned out to be just as opposed as the Ukrainian-speaking population.
The Ukrainians have put up an incredibly courageous resistance against an opponent that nothing seems to be able to stop.
In July 2021, Putin published a long essay arguing that Russians and Ukrainians are actually one people and that the Ukrainians have been deceived by neo-Nazi agitators.
The first part of his argument is not without historical justification, given that Kyiv was the original seat of the Russian Orthodox Church.
But in the second part, it was Putin who was misled.
He should have been more prudent.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the 2014 'Euromaidan protests.
The 2014 events plunged him into black anger.
But the Russian army performed poorly when it was ordered to attack its Ukrainian brothers.
The deeply rooted corruption in defense contract allocations also played an important role in his insufficient results.
Yet, instead of blaming himself, Putin seems to have become literally crazy.
He decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him and seems to be acting without facing any resistance.
He throws the entire Russian army into the battle and ignores all the rules of war, including indiscriminately bombing the civilian population.
Many hospitals have been hit, and the electrical grid powering the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian troops) has been damaged.
In besieged Mariupol, 400,000 people were without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia might well lose the war.
The United States and the European Union are sending defensive arms to Ukraine, and efforts are underway to purchase Russian-made MIG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
This could make all the difference.
Whatever the outcome, Putin has already achieved wonders in strengthening the determination and unity of the EU.
Meanwhile, Xi seems to have realized that Putin is acting alone.
On March 8, a day after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that the friendship between China and Russia remains "solid", Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to say he supported their peace-restoration efforts.
He wanted to express the maximum restraint in the war to avoid a humanitarian crisis.
It is far from certain that Putin will heed Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed before they destroy our civilization.
